<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="05a8f1e030a27ed02eb39d2106de8ec7" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Lord of the Rings TCG: Chaos Format<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.67)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10198'>George "urthanz" Wilson</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10198&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 29, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Lord of the Rings TCG - Chaos Format<br />
<br />
1. What the game represents.<br />
2. Point of the game.<br />
3. Starting the game.<br />
4. Phases.<br />
5. Specific Rules<br />
6. Example Deck<br />
<br />
1. What the Game Represents:<br />
<br />
This game is supposed to symbolize the chaos in middle-earth. A Kings of Chaos inspired game that is played for fun and requires its own strategies.<br />
<br />
2. Point of the Game:<br />
<br />
The point of this game is to survive to site 9 with the most life points (sort of a Magic concept). You play minions and characters along with their possessions and conditions to ruin your opponent. In order to beat the opponent, you must manage your people, while not overplaying them. You must also be cautious not to deck yourself out. As in Lotr TCG, you don&#8217;t lose when you deck yourself out, but you must try to get fresh minions and characters to beat down the opponent!<br />
<br />
3. Starting the Game:<br />
<br />
To play this game, you need Frodo, The One Ring, 9 Sites, 8 starting companions, a 52-card deck, and a paper and pen to keep score. To start the game, but both players&#8217; life points at 500. Here&#8217;s the criteria for your starting fellowship:<br />
<br />
The twilight total must equal 12. You need the following:<br />
1 non-unique Hobbit (Hobbit Party Guest, Bounder&#8230; Note: Hobbit allies are the only allies besides Thrarin that can fight)<br />
1 non-unique Dwarf (Dwarf Guard can be used and &#8220;to play, spot a Dwarf&#8221; is neglected)<br />
1 non-unique Elf (Lorien Elf can be used and &#8220;to play, spot an Elf&#8221; is neglected)<br />
1 non-unique Man (Gondorian Ranger, Rider of Rohan&#8230;)<br />
1 non-unique Shadow Man (Dunlending Ravager, Southron Scout&#8230;)<br />
1 non-unique Orc (Goblin Runner, Orc Slayer&#8230;)<br />
1 non-unique Uruk (Uruk Foot Soldier)<br />
1 unique Nazgul (Lemenya, Nertea, or Ostea)<br />
Frodo and the Ring (The Ring just adds strength or vitality, no burdens in this game)<br />
<br />
To start the game, you must draw a hand of 8 and when you reconcile, you may discard one card and even up back to 8. To decide who goes first, roll a die. Name both players either player 1 or player 2. Whoever wins gets to choose who goes first. If you go first, lose 10 life points. Play your site 1, and for the rest of the game, you move to your opponent&#8217;s sites. There&#8217;s no such thing as double-moving.<br />
<br />
4. Phases:<br />
<br />
There are many phases an subphases to know. Archery has been changed the most.<br />
<br />
DEPLOY: Play your Free Peoples characters (6 twilight per turn), play your shadow characters (10 twilight per turn), and your possessions and conditions (4 twilight per turn).<br />
<br />
MOVE: Subtract one life point for each character you can spot besides Frodo. If you do not meet your opponent at that site, you and your opponent reconcile and it&#8217;s your opponent&#8217;s turn, otherwise, move to the next phase.<br />
<br />
MANEUVER: Do all maneuver actions (Enquea&#8217;s really effective in this format).<br />
<br />
SKIRMISH: All __________s must battle. (limit X battles where X is the shadow number) If there are any ___________s left over, the player with the extra minion(s)/companion(s) may assign it/them with another one of their minions/companions. <br />
<br />
The order goes like this:<br />
1.Orcs (Moria Orcs, Mordor Orcs, Isengard Orcs&#8230;)<br />
2.Uruk-hai<br />
3.Shadow Men (Raiders, Dunland, Saruman, Isengard Men&#8230; Note: Saruman fights no matter what)<br />
4.Nazgul<br />
5.Free Peoples Men (Including Gandalf)<br />
6.Elves<br />
7.Dwarves<br />
8.Hobbits<br />
<br />
Each player assigns them face down to another minion/companion. Only Orcs may fight Orcs and so on&#8230; Exception: Dunlending Ravager and Warrior, Orc Assassin. When they&#8217;re assigned to, for example, a Hobbit ally, it counts as a Hobbit Assignment, and the minion isn&#8217;t counted as being in its own culture (Orc Assassin would count as being a Hobbit for the skirmish). For more questions about ties, point losses for deaths, other information, consult &#8220;Specific Rules&#8221; down below.<br />
<br />
ARCHERY: At the end of the skirmishes, each opponent must take archery wounds for each <B>Archer</B> present. Events and conditions that make the total +X are also allowed. Greenleaf, Orophin and Rumil, and Aragorn&#8217;s Bow are not.<br />
<br />
RECONCILE: Reconcile your hands.<br />
<br />
5. Specific Rules:<br />
<br />
POINT LOSS: Since you lose points throughout the game, here are the penalties:<br />
<br />
-X: 1 point deducted for each companion besides Frodo when you move.<br />
-Xx2: The shadow number doubled for each culture you&#8217;re missing that your opponent isn&#8217;t (once each skirmish phase).<br />
-5: 5 points deducted for each minion that died.<br />
-10: 10 points deducted for starting.<br />
-10: 10 points deducted for each companion that died (besides Frodo).<br />
-100: 100 points deducted for Frodo dead.<br />
<br />
KEYWORD CHANGED: 2 Keywords were changed to make better of this game.<br />
Fierce: If a character KILLS someone, reassign him to someone else (if a skirmish is unresolved, you can add him to that skirmish). Once per skirmish phase.<br />
Defender +1: Is immune to fighting to 2 characters at once.<br />
<br />
ASSIGNMENT: Characters are assigned face down. All extra minions assigned are put on face up.<br />
<br />
POSSESSIONS: Possessions are played to your support area, or in this game, &#8220;armory&#8221;. At the beginning of the culture&#8217;s skirmish phase, you may equip a minion/companion with a possession. If that companion dies, discard the possession. If he/she lives, put it back in your armory.<br />
<br />
UNIQUE: Characters that are unique (besides Frodo) cannot be played by the opponent. This is the advantage of going first, as you have the first chance to play unique companions, but you also must take 10 life points down the drain. When a unique possession is played, it cannot be played again, even if it&#8217;s discarded. You must bring 2 of the 3 possible starting Nazgul and possibly roll for the one that you want to play with. If a companion or minion is played that is unique, he or she cannot be played again, except for Merry and Pippin when they are discarded. As for the Ents, they don&#8217;t have a place yet, so wait for version 2 to play them!<br />
<br />
DICE: Dice play a big part in skirmishes. If there&#8217;s a tie, you must roll! Remember the part about naming yourself Player 1 or 2? Here&#8217;s where it comes in. You&#8217;ll need a D6.<br />
<br />
(1) = Skirmish Cancelled.<br />
(2) = Player 1 wins.<br />
(3) = Player 2 wins.<br />
(4) = Both players lose and must take the appropriate wounds from each other.<br />
(5) = Both players lose and must take 1 wound each.<br />
(6) = Both companions/minions die.<br />
<br />
6. Example Deck:<br />
<br />
Uruk Power<br />
<br />
Frodo, Old Bilbo&#8217;s Heir<br />
The One Ring, Isildur&#8217;s Bane<br />
Bounder<br />
Lorien Elf<br />
Dwarf Guard<br />
Rider of Rohan<br />
Uruk Foot Soldier<br />
Dunlending Ravager<br />
Orc Slayer<br />
Ulaire Ostea (or Nertea if you can&#8217;t get it)<br />
<br />
1) The Riddermark<br />
2) Plains of Rohan Camp<br />
3) Golden Hall<br />
4) Ered Nimrais<br />
5) Deep of Helm<br />
6) Hornburg Armory<br />
7) King&#8217;s Room<br />
8) Wizard&#8217;s Vale<br />
9) Fortress of Orthanc<br />
<br />
Legolas, Elven Comrade x2<br />
Gimli, Dwarf of the Mountain-Race<br />
Gloin<br />
Fror<br />
Dwarven Axe x2<br />
Asfaloth<br />
Bow of the Galadhrim<br />
Aragorn, King in Exile x2<br />
Boromir, Lord of Gondor<br />
Faramir, Son of Denethor<br />
Sword of Gondor x2<br />
Flaming Brand<br />
No Stranger to the Shadows (actually reduces the site number for less battles)<br />
Merry, Horticulturalist<br />
Farmer Maggot<br />
Sam, Proper Poet x2<br />
The Gaffer<br />
Hobbit Sword x3<br />
Orc Assassin x4 (Champ)<br />
Uruk Chaser x4<br />
Uruk Plains Runner x4<br />
Ugluk<br />
Uruk Follower<br />
Uruk Vanguard<br />
Saruman, Servant of the Eye x2<br />
Ugluk&#8217;s Sword<br />
Uruk Spear x2<br />
Broad-Bladed Swordx2<br />
Ulaire Enquea, Lieutenant of Morgul x2<br />
Ulaire Nelya, Lieutenant of Morgul<br />
Ulaire Nertea<br />
<br />
After playtesting this format, I REALLY enjoyed myself! I hope that you can play this awesome game of its own sometime (maybe with a friend). I know that I&#8217;m going to push this at my local tournament! <br />
<br />
Ciao,<br />
Urthanz<br />
